{"content":"#!/usr/bin/perl
use strict;
use warnings;

my $pattern;
open my $fh, '<', '/app/regex.txt' or die "Cannot read regex.txt: $!";
$pattern = <$fh>;
close $fh;
chomp $pattern;

print "Pattern loaded. Length: ", length($pattern), "\n";

my $log_text = <<'ENDLOG';
2024-01-15 Server 192.168.1.1 started
2024-03-20 User connected from 10.0.0.1 at 2024-06-15
2024-01-01 Event A 2024-12-31 Event B 172.16.0.1
user 1134-12-1234 is not a date
2024-02-29 Leap year day 192.0.0.1
2024-13-01 Invalid month should not match
2024-06-31 Invalid day should not match
2024-04-30 April has 30 days
2024-05-32 May has max 31 days
x2024-01-01 preceded by alpha should not match
2024-01-01x followed by alpha should not match
0192.168.1.1 leading zero in IP should not match
192.168.01.1 leading zero in IP should not match
ENDLOG

my @matches;
while ($log_text =~ /^.*$pattern.*$/gm) {
    # Perl doesn't have re.MULTILINE flag, but /m does multiline mode
}

# Use a different approach - split by lines and test each
my @lines = split /\n/, $log_text;
for my $line (@lines) {
    if ($line =~ /$pattern/) {
        push @matches, $1;
    }
}

print "\nMatches: ", scalar(@matches), "\n";
for my $m (@matches) {
    print "  '$m'\n";
}
","path":"/app/test_regex.pl"}

function.description:
MUST be your first tool call on any action task. Records the definition-of-done as a list of testable assertions, each ≤120 chars. After this returns, `write_file` / `patch` / mutating `bash` become available.

EXAMPLE — for the prompt "write /app/foo.py that prints 42":
{
"title": "foo.py prints 42",
"brief": "Create /app/foo.py so that `python3 /app/foo.py` writes `42` to stdout.",
"assertions": [
{"id": "A.001", "text": "/app/foo.py exists"},
{"id": "A.002", "text": "running /app/foo.py prints exactly '42'"}
]
}

Rules: 2-6 assertions, each a single concrete check (file exists / a command exits 0 / output contains X). NO vague ones like "works correctly". Skip wrapping prose.
